The Porte Saint-Denis is a Parisian monument located in the 10th arrondissement, at the site of one of the gates of the Wall of Charles V, one of Paris' former city walls. It is located at the crossing of the Rue Saint-Denis continued by the Rue du Faubourg Saint-Denis, with the Boulevard de Bonne-Nouvelle and the Boulevard Saint-Denis. The Porte Saint-Denis was the first of four triumphal arches to be built in Paris. The three others are the Arc de Triomphe du Carrousel (1806-1808), Porte Saint-Martin (1674), and Arc de Triomphe (1836).

A historical monument that looks a bit like the Arc de Triomphe  ‚Äî  Porte Saint-Denis is a French triumphal arch located near Rue Faubourg Saint-Denis in the 10th arrondissement of Paris. The original site of Porte Saint-Denis was one of the gates of the city wall of Charles V. It was once a fortification of Paris. The closest station to Porte Saint-Denis is Strasbourg-Saint-Denis.  The Porte Saint-Denis was designed by architect Fran√ßois Blondel. Louis XIV ordered the sculptors Brother Angier to carve a statue of the Arc de Triomphe on the Porte Saint-Denis in 1674 to commemorate Louis XIV's victory on the Rhine and Franche-Comt√©. The Porte Saint-Denis was built in 1672 to replace the city gate built by Charles V in the 14th century. The Porte Saint-Denis is the most influential building in Blondel. It was renovated in 1988.

This is the Porte Saint-Denis, one of the triumphal arches. This gate, like the nearby Porta Saint-Martin, is part of the city wall from the time of Charles V. It was converted into a triumphal arch during the reign of Louis XIV to celebrate the victory of the Franco-Dutch War. The text The above reads "Dedicated to Louis the Great". Because it is located in a relatively busy area, many tourists would not consider visiting. If I hadn't happened to pass by, I might have missed this landmark with profound historical significance. ‚ÄúThe gate is a triumphal arch, inspired by the Roman Arch of Titus. Above the gate passage are two bas-reliefs by Michel Anguier, depicting moments from the Dutch War. The crossing of the Rhine (1672) is depicted on the south side and the Capture of Maastricht by Louis XIV (1673) on the north side. On both sides there is an allegorical image of the conquered Dutch Republic: the Dutch lion with its tongue hanging out of its mouth.‚Äù
